<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0064 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0615EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-01 0593</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0611</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Mainly on the Plains; Light Snow in Rockies</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm that whipped up a tornado, hail and wind gusts up to 59mph in Texas and New Mexico spread rain and snow today across theGreat Plains.   A tornado touched down Thursday evening northwest of Hobbs,N.M., damaging an unoccupied barn and house trailer.   In northwest Texas, golfball-size hail fell near Woodrow,Brownfield, Post and Denver City. Two inches of penny-size hailcovered the ground at Odonnell late Thursday. Lubbock recorded awind gust of 59 mph.   The southerly flow of moist air from the Gulf of Mexico broughtheavy rain to some areas. More than 2.5 inches fell late Thursdaynear Walnut and Cherryvale, Kan.   Forecasters posted flash flood watches for much of southeastKansas, parts of Oklahoma and parts of Mississippi.   The rainfall at Wichita Falls, Texas, brought the total rainfallfor March to 5.24 inches, its wettest month on record. The previousrecord was 4.71 inches set in 1905.   Omaha, Neb., however, had its driest March since 1910 with just.07 inches of rain, but forecasters said substantial rainfall wasexpected through Saturday.   Snow continued this morning in parts of the southern Rockies.Albuquerque, N.M., had 4 inches of snow on the ground by midnightand Edgewood, N.M., had 7 inches.   In Colorado, the storm began easing after dropping 20 inches ofsnow at Rye, 15 inches at Buelah, 13 inches at Silver Cliff and 9inches east of Salida. Seven inches fell on the Denver area.Forecasters predicted another 1 to 4 inches of snow in Coloradotoday.   A snow advisory was posted for northwestern Kansas, and a freezewarning was in effect in southeast Arizona above elevations of4,000 feet.   Today's forecast called for widespread rain and thunderstormsacross Kansas, Oklahoma, parts of Texas and the Mississippi andTennessee valleys; showers and a few thundershowers from the OhioValley to the middle Atlantic Coast and across southern Michiganand New York state; thunderstorms from Alabama into the westernCarolinas; snow across Colorado, northern New Mexico, parts of theTexas and Oklahoma panhandles and northwest Kansas.   Highs will be in the 50s or 60s in much of the nation; 30s and40s from the central High Plains and the Texas panhandle across thecentral Rockies to northern Arizona, and Michigan to northernMinnesota; 70s and low 80s from California to the desert Southwest,and from southern and eastern Texas across the lower Mississippiand Tennessee valleys and the southern Appalachians to the southAtlantic states.   The high for the nation Thursday was 91 degrees at Presidio,Texas.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 9degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 75 degrees at Key West, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 62 cloudy; Boston 44 cloudy; Buffalo 44 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 61 fair; Cincinnati 53 rain; Cleveland 41 cloudy;Detroit 41 cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York 45 partly cloudy;Philadelphia 49 cloudy; Pittsburgh 53 foggy; Portland, Maine, 31partly cloudy; Washington 53 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 30 partly cloudy; Chicago 41 partly cloudy;Dallas-Fort Worth 65 cloudy; Denver 20 cloudy; Des Moines 47cloudy; Indianapolis 48 rain; Kansas City 45 rain; Minneapolis-St.Paul 30 fair; Nashville 57 rain; New Orleans 64 partly cloudy; St.Louis 50 foggy.   _West: Albuquerque 31 snow; Anchorage 32 cloudy; Las Vegas 46fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 55 fair; Salt Lake City 35 fair;San Diego 58 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 46 partly cloudy.   _Canada: Toronto 34 partly cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>